            <a:r>
              <a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/>
              <a:t>So observability is layered, which is a design choice we made intentionally. Every significant action emits a typed RuntimeEvent — think of it like a structured log entry with event_type, session_id, job_id, and an open dict for custom data. These events fan out through RuntimeEventSink implementations. In tests and basic mode, they get dropped. In production, we fan out to multiple sinks simultaneously: base sinks get every event, per-session sinks only get their session's events. Langfuse integration hooks in automatically — when you set LANGFUSE_PUBLIC_KEY and SECRET, LLM traces flow there with zero code changes. And we have timed_span(), a context manager to measure latency on any code block without changing the structure.</a:t>
            </a:r>
          </a:p>
        </p:txBody>
